    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:48928003-cbe4-48ed-bae7-fed0ae392e43",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 38-year-old man who looks tired but still tries to appear composed, sitting forward on the exam table with one hand resting over the right upper side of his abdomen. His skin has a faint yellow cast that is most noticeable in the sclera, and he moves a bit cautiously because of persistent nausea, abdominal discomfort, and a deep sense of fatigue that has been worsening over the last two weeks. He describes dark urine, poor appetite, and intermittent low-grade fevers, saying he initially thought he had a stomach bug until the exhaustion and abdominal fullness began interfering with daily life.\n\nHe works as a warehouse shift supervisor, a job that keeps him physically active but also leaves him with irregular meal patterns and poor sleep during busy periods. Outside work he enjoys recreational softball, grilling with friends, and taking weekend fishing trips with his brother. He lives with his partner and young son, and his family has recently noticed that he has been more withdrawn, sleeping on the couch after work and skipping social plans because he feels drained.\n\n{patientName} drinks alcohol socially, usually beer on weekends, but denies heavy daily use. Over the past month he has relied more on over-the-counter pain relievers for muscle aches after work. He does not smoke cigarettes and denies illicit drug use. His diet is inconsistent, often heavy in takeout meals during workweeks, though he says he normally tries to stay active. The combination of fatigue, nausea, and jaundice has made him worried that something is seriously wrong with his liver.\n\nOn examination he appears mildly ill but not toxic, alert and cooperative, with mild right upper quadrant tenderness and no obvious confusion or signs of severe chronic liver failure. He is anxious about the possibility of long-term liver damage and asks repeatedly whether the condition is reversible."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:1e29fbae-f4ea-4cab-8eaf-0e96825f4258",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no known chronic liver disease and no prior history of cirrhosis, hepatitis diagnosis, or hepatic decompensation. He has a history of obesity class I and intermittent dyspepsia but has otherwise been generally healthy. He was evaluated in the emergency department once 3 years ago for dehydration after viral gastroenteritis but has had no major hospitalizations. Over the last several weeks he reports increasing fatigue, reduced appetite, nausea, dark urine, and mild pruritus, followed by noticeable yellowing of the eyes.\n\nHe reports occasional weekend alcohol intake, usually 4 to 6 beers across a weekend, and recent use of over-the-counter analgesics for musculoskeletal aches after physical work. He denies intravenous drug use, high-risk sexual exposures, or recent international travel. He has no history of blood transfusions. He is not taking chronic prescription medications. His symptoms are limiting work attendance and exercise tolerance, and he has become more sedentary since the onset of illness."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
